{{Advanced Placement}}
'''AP Physics C: Electricity and Magnetism''' (Also commonly referred to as '''AP Physics C: E&M''', or simply '''E&M''') is an [[Advanced Placement Program|Advanced Placement]] [[science]] course about [[electricity]] and [[magnetism]]. It is one of the four [[AP Physics]] courses offered in some [[Secondary education in the United States|U.S. secondary schools]].
==Course content==
It is supposed to be equivalent to an introductory [[college]] course in [[electricity]] and [[magnetism]] for physics or engineering majors.<ref name=PhysCe&mOverview>{{citation | url = http://media.collegeboard.com/digitalServices/pdf/ap/ap-course-overviews/ap-physics-c-mechanics-course-overview.pdf | format = PDF | title = AP® PHYSICS C: ELECTRICITY & MAGNETISM | publisher = [[College Board]] | date = December 2016 | access-date = January 30, 2017}}</ref> The course modules are:<ref name=PhysCe&mOverview /> * Electrostatics * Conductors, capacitors, and dielectrics * Electric circuits * Magnetic fields * Electromagnetism.
Methods of [[calculus]] are used wherever appropriate in formulating physical principles and in applying them to physical problems. Therefore, students should have completed or be concurrently enrolled in a calculus class.<ref name=PhysCe&mOverview />
This course may be combined with [[AP Physics C: Mechanics]] to make a unified Physics C course that prepares for both exams. In this scenario, Electricity and Magnetism is typically taught second, as it requires much of the knowledge gained in the Mechanics course.
==AP test== The course culminates in an optional exam for which high-performing students may receive some credit towards their college coursework, depending on which college or university they attend.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://apstudent.collegeboard.org/creditandplacement | title = Credit & Placement | work = AP Students | publisher = The [[College Board]] | year = 2017 | access-date = January 30, 2017}}</ref>
===Registration=== The AP examination for AP Physics C: Electricity and Magnetism is separate from the AP examination for AP Physics C: Mechanics. Before 2006, test-takers paid only once and were given the choice of taking either one or two parts of the Physics C test.
===Format=== The exam is configured in two categories: a 35-question [[multiple choice]] section and a 3-question [[free response]] section.<ref name=PhysCe&mOverview /> Test takers are allowed to use an approved calculator during the entire exam.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://apstudent.collegeboard.org/apcourse/ap-physics-c-mechanics/calculator-and-table-policies | title = AP Physics C: Mechanics – Calculator and Table Policies | work = AP Students | publisher = [[College Board]] | year = 2017 | access-date = January 30, 2017}}</ref> The test is weighted such that each section is worth half of the final score.<ref name=PhysCe&mOverview /> This and [[AP Physics C: Mechanics]] are the shortest AP exams, with total testing time of 90 minutes.<ref name=PhysCe&mOverview />
The topics covered by the exam are as follows:<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.collegeboard.com/student/testing/ap/physics_c/topics.html | title = Topic Outline | work = College Board Tests | publisher = The College Board | year = 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130404054146/http://www.collegeboard.com/student/testing/ap/physics_c/topics.html | archive-date = April 4, 2013}}</ref>
